SIMPLE: rut
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rut
<hw>Rut</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>rut</ets>, OF.
<ets>ruit</ets>, L. <ets>rugitus</ets> a roaring, fr. <ets>rugire</ets>
to roar; -- so called from the noise made by deer in rutting
time.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>Sexual desire or
oestrus of deer, cattle, and various other mammals; heat; also, the
period during which the oestrus exists.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Roaring, as of waves breaking upon the shore; rote.
See <er>Rote</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rut</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rut
<hw>Rut</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Rutted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Rutting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To have a strong sexual impulse
at the reproductive period; -- said of deer, cattle, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rut</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Rut
<hw>Rut</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cover in copulation.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rut</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Rut
<hw>Rut</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[variant of <ets>route</ets>.]</ety>
<def>A track worn by a wheel or by habitual passage of anything; a
groove in which anything runs. Also used figuratively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- (Fig.) Habitual, unvarying activity -- usually used in the phrase
<it>in a rut</it>. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rut</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Rut
<hw>Rut</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make a rut or ruts in; -- chiefly
used as a past participle or a participial adj.; <as>as, a
<ex>rutted</ex> road</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ruta-baga</ent>⟦br⟧
